        <title data-rh="true">cohost! - &quot;THE ℤ₂ GAMBIT&quot;</title>
        <meta data-rh="true" name="apple-mobile-web-app-title" content="cohost"/><meta data-rh="true" name="application-name" content="cohost"/><meta data-rh="true" name="theme-color" content="#671A3D" media="(max-width: 1023px)"/><meta data-rh="true" name="theme-color" content="#83254f"/><meta data-rh="true" property="og:site_name" content="cassie on cohost"/><meta data-rh="true" property="og:title" content="THE ℤ₂ GAMBIT"/><meta data-rh="true" property="og:description" content="I solved this puzzle properly, by hand! It only took like four hours.

You know there&#x27;s a simple algorithm for this puzzle: you just have to construct and solve a 54x54 linear system in ℤ₂! Each cell influences some subset of the other cells (and sets them to 1), so you make a column out of each cell to form a matrix 𝐀, as well as a vector for the solution 𝐛, and then solve 𝐀𝐱 + 𝐛 = 0 in ℤ₂.

More in-depth details below the cut, I&#x27;ll explain all of that at least briefly for folks who don&#x27;t know what those terms mean. And you won&#x27;t see the solution unless you want to, if you want to try this method for yourself.

----------------------------------------

The first part: we want to model toggling things on and off so we can handle the lights here. Luckily, mathematicians have our back, the set of numbers ℤ₂ represents that well. In it, there are only two numbers, 0 and 1, and addition works the same as usual except that 1 + 1 = 0 — so adding 1 to a number toggles it on and off. Multiplying is completely normal.

Next, we need a bunch of equations to figure out whether each square is toggled. We give each square a name so we can write about their relations: Let&#x27;s say:

 * square 𝑥₀ is toggled by squares 𝑥₀, 𝑥₁, 𝑥₅, and 𝑥₈
 * it&#x27;s initially on in the puzzle
 * we want to turn it off (because it&#x27;s &quot;Lights Out&quot;)

We can write that equation as: 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₅ + 𝑥₈ + 1 = 0. Conveniently, we can add 1 to both sides of this equation, and get 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₅ + 𝑥₈ = 1, which is slightly nicer to work with later. We can make one equation like this for each cell in the grid, and then solve them all simultaneously.

Let&#x27;s find an actual one of these equations, looking at the very first cell:

