e right page is part of the diagonal of a sparse binary matrix, but I've given up because it's like 30% too big to easily fit on the page.","previewURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Fattachment\u002Fd816dd27-bb6e-4f03-a95a-dac7ba8d6d0a\u002FIMG_5938.jpg","fileURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Fattachment\u002Fd816dd27-bb6e-4f03-a95a-dac7ba8d6d0a\u002FIMG_5938.jpg","kind":"image","width":4032,"height":3024}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"I solved this puzzle properly, by hand! It only took like four hours."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"You know there's a simple algorithm for this puzzle: you just have to construct and solve a 54x54 linear system in ℤ₂! Each cell influences some subset of the other cells (and sets them to 1), so you make a column out of each cell to form a matrix 𝐀, as well as a vector for the solution 𝐛, and then solve 𝐀𝐱 + 𝐛 = 0 in ℤ₂."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"More in-depth details below the cut, I'll explain all of that at least *briefly* for folks who don't know what those terms mean. And you won't see the solution unless you want to, if you want to try this method for yourself."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"---"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"The first part: we want to model toggling things on and off so we can handle the lights here.\nLuckily, mathematicians have our back, the set of numbers ℤ₂ represents that well.\nIn it, there are only two numbers, 0 and 1, and addition works the same as usual except that 1 + 1 = 0 — so adding 1 to a number toggles it on and off.\nMultiplying is completely normal."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"Next, we need a bunch of equations to figure out whether each square is toggled.\nWe give each square a name so we can write about their relations:\nLet's say:"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"- square 𝑥₀ is toggled by squares 𝑥₀, 𝑥₁, 𝑥₅, and 𝑥₈\n- it's initially on in the puzzle\n- we want to turn it off (because it's \"Lights Out\")"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"We can write that equation as: 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₅ + 𝑥₈ + 1 = 0.\nConveniently, we can add 1 to both sides of this equation, and get 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₅ + 𝑥₈ = 1, which is slightly nicer to work with later.\nWe can make one equation like this for each cell in the grid, and then solve them all simultaneously."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"Let's find an actual one of these equations, looking at the very first cell:\n```\n100000\n010000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n```\nWe can unwrap this into a straight line that represents all of the cells it impacts:\n```\n100000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000\n```\nThis isn't quite what we want for making our equations, instead of telling us what cells impact the first cell, this tells us which cells the first cell impacts.\nHowever, we can find this information pretty easily!"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"If we do this process for each cell on the board, we get 54 (6x9) of these 54-entry vectors.\nIf we use these as *columns* of a matrix, we end up with columns that represent all of the cells that a given cell impacts, and the rows representing all of the cells that impacts *that cell*.\nWe do the same unwrapping for the initial state of the board, and set that column next to our matrix, to give us an \"augmented matrix\" for solving the system."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"If we look at the first row of our matrix, we've got:\n```\n110000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n```\nJust to make it clear on last time, this tells us all the cells that toggle the first cell 𝑥₀.\nTurning this back into an equation, we get: 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₆ = 1."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"But we're going to want to work directly with the matrix, since it's much easier to solve as a matrix than as a bunch of separate equations."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\u003Cdetails\u003E\n\u003Csummary\u003EThe full linear system for this puzzle\u003C\u002Fsummary\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"```\n110000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n011000011000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n011000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000100000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000010000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000011000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n010000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n100000110000110000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n001000011000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000110000110001010000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000111000010000110000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000001000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000100000110000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000001000111000011000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000011000011000001100000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000110000100001110000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000110000111000110000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000011000011000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000010000110000100000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000111000010000101000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000010000011100010100000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000100001100001110000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000101000111000011000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000001000011000011000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000110000100000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000110000110000001000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000010000001100011100000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000001100000110001110000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000001000011000001000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000010000001000011000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000100000100000110000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000110000110000110000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000100011100010000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000001000000100000100000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000010000011000011000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000011000011000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000010000100000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000001000011000011000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000100011000011100000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000001100000100001100000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000110000010000011000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000001000001000001000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000010000100000010000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000101000010000001000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000011000001000011100|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000001110000100001100|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000011000010|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000011000001000010|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000100000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000011000011000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100001100|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000111|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000011000001|1\n```"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\u003C\u002Fdetails\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"This big matrix represents the vector equation 𝐜₀𝑥₀ + 𝐜₁𝑥₁ + … + 𝐜₅₃𝑥₅₃ = 𝐛, which you can think of as either a bunch of equations, one for each cell, or one equation acting on the whole board.\nIt says \"𝑥₀ decides if you toggle cells 𝐜₀, 𝑥₁ decides if you toggle the cells 𝐜₁, and so on, and after all the toggling, we want to toggle exactly the cells in the initial board 𝐛.\""}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"You can solve this with [Gaussian elimination](https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FGaussian_elimination), which is luckily much easier in ℤ₂ since you only have to toggle between 0 and 1 instead of doing full addition."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"- First, try to get it into row-echelon form, which means you need to try to make the lower left triangle of the matrix all zeroes. (If you manage it, it will automatically be in reduced form since there are no numbers besides 0 and 1).\n- In broad terms, you want to add the rows with a leading number along the diagonal to any rows below them that have a 1 in that column, and slowly get rid of all of the 1s in the lower triangle.\n- You need to swap some rows to make sure you keep having entries along the diagonal.\n- You can find more detailed explanations of this elsewhere.\n  (This is hopefully a little reminder for people who might have learned this in school and half-remember it?)"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"I did this mostly by hand, but I kept making little typos so I wrote a program that would execute the row operations for me. I still made all the decisions, but it prevented me from making any typos—if this were smaller (maybe a standard 5x5 board ⇒ 25x25 matrix) I would've stuck to fully doing it by hand, for fun."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\u003Cdetails\u003E\n\u003Csummary\u003EThe row operations helper script I used\u003C\u002Fsummary\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\u003Cpre style=\"background-color:rgb(40, 43, 46);color:rgb(224, 226, 228);position:relative;padding:0;line-height:1.2rem;margin-bottom:0;box-shadow:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2) 1px 2px 4px 0px\"\u003E\u003Cdiv style=\"opacity:.8;transform:translateY(-10.25px)scale(0.75);cursor:default;top:19px;left:16px;pointer-events:none;position:absolute;transform-origin:left top;line-height:1.15rem;fony-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible,ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,segoe ui,Roboto,helvetica neue,Arial,noto sans,sans-serif,apple color emoji,segoe ui emoji,segoe ui symbol,noto color emoji\"\u003Elinear_system.py\u003C\u002Fdiv\u003E\u003Ccode style=\"padding:0 16px;display:block;margin-bottom:9px;margin-top:23px\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003EMATRIX_INPUT = \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;&quot;&quot;\n(put your linear system in this string)\n&quot;&quot;&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E.strip().splitlines()"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\n\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Edef\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"font-weight: bold\"\u003Eapply\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E(a: str, b: str)\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E -&gt; str:\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;&quot;&quot;\n    Does xor on two augmented lines\n    &gt;&gt;&gt; apply(&quot;11010|0&quot;, &quot;10110|1&quot;)\n    &#39;01100|1&#39;\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ereturn\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E.join(\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;|&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E x == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;|&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eelse\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E str(int(x) ^ int(y))\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E x, y \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E zip(a, b)\n    )"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\n\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Edef\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"font-weight: bold\"\u003Eshow\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E(lines: list[str])\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E -&gt; \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ENone\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    pad = len(str(len(lines)))\n    \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E i, line \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E enumerate(lines):\n        print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003Ef&quot;\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(140, 187, 173)\"\u003E{i:&gt;{pad}\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E} \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(140, 187, 173)\"\u003E{line}\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\n\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Edef\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"font-weight: bold\"\u003Eshow_help\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E()\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E -&gt; \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ENone\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;help - show this output&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)\n    print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;add a b [b ...] - add row a to all rows indexed b&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)\n    print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;move a b - move row a before row b&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\n\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Edef\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"font-weight: bold\"\u003Emain\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E(matrix_input)\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E -&gt; \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ENone\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    matrix = [line \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E line \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E matrix_input]"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"    first_time = \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ETrue\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ewhile\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ETrue\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n        show(matrix)\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E first_time:\n            show_help()\n            first_time = \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003EFalse\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Etry\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n            cmd = input(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;&gt; &quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eexcept\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E KeyboardInterrupt:\n            \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ebreak\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Etry\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n            cmd, *args = cmd.split()\n            \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E cmd == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;help&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n                show_help()\n            \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eelif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E cmd == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;add&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n                a = int(args[\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(255, 205, 34)\"\u003E0\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E])\n                \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(129, 142, 150)\"\u003E# Use a list comprehension to force it to fail early\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n                bs = [int(b) \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E b \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E args[\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(255, 205, 34)\"\u003E1\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:]]\n                \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E b \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E bs:\n                    matrix[b] = apply(matrix[a], matrix[b])\n            \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eelif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E cmd == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;move&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n                a, b = args\n                a, b = int(a), int(b)\n                row = matrix.pop(a)\n                matrix.insert(b, row)\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eexcept\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n            print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;Error in command&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\n\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E __name__ == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;__main__&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n    main(MATRIX_INPUT)\n\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fpre\u003E\u003Cdiv style=\"text-align: right; font-size: min(1.87vw, 70%); opacity: 0.7; margin-bottom: 1.7142857em;\"\u003Emade with @nex3's \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fnex3.github.io\u002Fcohost-highlight\"\u003Esyntax highlighter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fdiv\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\u003C\u002Fdetails\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"In this case, I had to arbitrarily assign two of the variables, because this puzzles seems slightly under-constrained (I believe this means there are 4—very similar—valid solutions). Once you get a fully solved matrix out:"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\u003Cdetails\u003E\n\u003Csummary\u003EThe fully solved matrix\u003C\u002Fsummary\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"```\n100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000010000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000001000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000100000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000010000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000001000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000100000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000010000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000001000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000100000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000010000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000001000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000100000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000010000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000001000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000100000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000010000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000001000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000100000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000010000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000001000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000100000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000010000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000001000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000100000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001|0\n```"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\u003C\u002Fdetails\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"We can pull the solution back out of this grid, taking the column on the right and wrapping it back up into a grid."}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\u003Cdetails\u003E\n\u003Csummary\u003E(Spoilers) The solution vector, as a board\u003C\u002Fsummary\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"```\n000101\n110100\n010001\n000100\n110100\n010000\n110001\n010110\n110100\n```"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"\u003C\u002Fdetails\u003E"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"And that works perfectly :D"}},{"type":"markdown","markdown":{"content":"One final note: This suggests a hell method for producing these puzzles.\nAny solvable linear system here generates a puzzle.\nFor this one, since everything only affected its neighborhood, the matrix was very sparse.\nBut if you made an extremely non-sparse matrix, you'd get any cell potentially toggling any other cell.\nEnjoy :)"}}],"plainTextBody":"I solved this puzzle properly, by hand! It only took like four hours.\n\nYou know there's a simple algorithm for this puzzle: you just have to construct and solve a 54x54 linear system in ℤ₂! Each cell influences some subset of the other cells (and sets them to 1), so you make a column out of each cell to form a matrix 𝐀, as well as a vector for the solution 𝐛, and then solve 𝐀𝐱 + 𝐛 = 0 in ℤ₂.\n\nMore in-depth details below the cut, I'll explain all of that at least *briefly* for folks who don't know what those terms mean. And you won't see the solution unless you want to, if you want to try this method for yourself.\n\n---\n\nThe first part: we want to model toggling things on and off so we can handle the lights here.\nLuckily, mathematicians have our back, the set of numbers ℤ₂ represents that well.\nIn it, there are only two numbers, 0 and 1, and addition works the same as usual except that 1 + 1 = 0 — so adding 1 to a number toggles it on and off.\nMultiplying is completely normal.\n\nNext, we need a bunch of equations to figure out whether each square is toggled.\nWe give each square a name so we can write about their relations:\nLet's say:\n\n- square 𝑥₀ is toggled by squares 𝑥₀, 𝑥₁, 𝑥₅, and 𝑥₈\n- it's initially on in the puzzle\n- we want to turn it off (because it's \"Lights Out\")\n\nWe can write that equation as: 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₅ + 𝑥₈ + 1 = 0.\nConveniently, we can add 1 to both sides of this equation, and get 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₅ + 𝑥₈ = 1, which is slightly nicer to work with later.\nWe can make one equation like this for each cell in the grid, and then solve them all simultaneously.\n\nLet's find an actual one of these equations, looking at the very first cell:\n```\n100000\n010000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n000000\n```\nWe can unwrap this into a straight line that represents all of the cells it impacts:\n```\n100000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000\n```\nThis isn't quite what we want for making our equations, instead of telling us what cells impact the first cell, this tells us which cells the first cell impacts.\nHowever, we can find this information pretty easily!\n\nIf we do this process for each cell on the board, we get 54 (6x9) of these 54-entry vectors.\nIf we use these as *columns* of a matrix, we end up with columns that represent all of the cells that a given cell impacts, and the rows representing all of the cells that impacts *that cell*.\nWe do the same unwrapping for the initial state of the board, and set that column next to our matrix, to give us an \"augmented matrix\" for solving the system.\n\nIf we look at the first row of our matrix, we've got:\n```\n110000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n```\nJust to make it clear on last time, this tells us all the cells that toggle the first cell 𝑥₀.\nTurning this back into an equation, we get: 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₆ = 1.\n\nBut we're going to want to work directly with the matrix, since it's much easier to solve as a matrix than as a bunch of separate equations.\n\n\u003Cdetails\u003E\n\u003Csummary\u003EThe full linear system for this puzzle\u003C\u002Fsummary\u003E\n\n```\n110000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n011000011000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n011000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000100000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000010000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000011000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n010000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n100000110000110000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n001000011000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000110000110001010000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000111000010000110000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000001000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000100000110000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000001000111000011000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000011000011000001100000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000110000100001110000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000110000111000110000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000011000011000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000010000110000100000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000111000010000101000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000010000011100010100000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000100001100001110000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000101000111000011000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000001000011000011000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000110000100000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000110000110000001000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000010000001100011100000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000001100000110001110000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000001000011000001000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000010000001000011000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000100000100000110000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000110000110000110000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000100011100010000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000001000000100000100000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000010000011000011000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000011000011000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000010000100000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000001000011000011000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000100011000011100000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000001100000100001100000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000110000010000011000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000001000001000001000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000010000100000010000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000101000010000001000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000011000001000011100|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000001110000100001100|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000011000010|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000011000001000010|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000100000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000011000011000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100001100|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000111|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000011000001|1\n```\n\n\u003C\u002Fdetails\u003E\n\nThis big matrix represents the vector equation 𝐜₀𝑥₀ + 𝐜₁𝑥₁ + … + 𝐜₅₃𝑥₅₃ = 𝐛, which you can think of as either a bunch of equations, one for each cell, or one equation acting on the whole board.\nIt says \"𝑥₀ decides if you toggle cells 𝐜₀, 𝑥₁ decides if you toggle the cells 𝐜₁, and so on, and after all the toggling, we want to toggle exactly the cells in the initial board 𝐛.\"\n\nYou can solve this with [Gaussian elimination](https:\u002F\u002Fen.wikipedia.org\u002Fwiki\u002FGaussian_elimination), which is luckily much easier in ℤ₂ since you only have to toggle between 0 and 1 instead of doing full addition.\n\n- First, try to get it into row-echelon form, which means you need to try to make the lower left triangle of the matrix all zeroes. (If you manage it, it will automatically be in reduced form since there are no numbers besides 0 and 1).\n- In broad terms, you want to add the rows with a leading number along the diagonal to any rows below them that have a 1 in that column, and slowly get rid of all of the 1s in the lower triangle.\n- You need to swap some rows to make sure you keep having entries along the diagonal.\n- You can find more detailed explanations of this elsewhere.\n  (This is hopefully a little reminder for people who might have learned this in school and half-remember it?)\n\nI did this mostly by hand, but I kept making little typos so I wrote a program that would execute the row operations for me. I still made all the decisions, but it prevented me from making any typos—if this were smaller (maybe a standard 5x5 board ⇒ 25x25 matrix) I would've stuck to fully doing it by hand, for fun.\n\n\u003Cdetails\u003E\n\u003Csummary\u003EThe row operations helper script I used\u003C\u002Fsummary\u003E\n\n\u003Cpre style=\"background-color:rgb(40, 43, 46);color:rgb(224, 226, 228);position:relative;padding:0;line-height:1.2rem;margin-bottom:0;box-shadow:rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.2) 1px 2px 4px 0px\"\u003E\u003Cdiv style=\"opacity:.8;transform:translateY(-10.25px)scale(0.75);cursor:default;top:19px;left:16px;pointer-events:none;position:absolute;transform-origin:left top;line-height:1.15rem;fony-family:Atkinson Hyperlegible,ui-sans-serif,system-ui,-apple-system,BlinkMacSystemFont,segoe ui,Roboto,helvetica neue,Arial,noto sans,sans-serif,apple color emoji,segoe ui emoji,segoe ui symbol,noto color emoji\"\u003Elinear_system.py\u003C\u002Fdiv\u003E\u003Ccode style=\"padding:0 16px;display:block;margin-bottom:9px;margin-top:23px\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003EMATRIX_INPUT = \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;&quot;&quot;\n(put your linear system in this string)\n&quot;&quot;&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E.strip().splitlines()\n\n\n\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Edef\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"font-weight: bold\"\u003Eapply\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E(a: str, b: str)\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E -&gt; str:\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;&quot;&quot;\n    Does xor on two augmented lines\n    &gt;&gt;&gt; apply(&quot;11010|0&quot;, &quot;10110|1&quot;)\n    &#39;01100|1&#39;\n    &quot;&quot;&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ereturn\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E.join(\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;|&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E x == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;|&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eelse\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E str(int(x) ^ int(y))\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E x, y \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E zip(a, b)\n    )\n\n\n\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Edef\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"font-weight: bold\"\u003Eshow\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E(lines: list[str])\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E -&gt; \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ENone\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    pad = len(str(len(lines)))\n    \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E i, line \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E enumerate(lines):\n        print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003Ef&quot;\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(140, 187, 173)\"\u003E{i:&gt;{pad}\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E} \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(140, 187, 173)\"\u003E{line}\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)\n\n\n\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Edef\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"font-weight: bold\"\u003Eshow_help\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E()\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E -&gt; \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ENone\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;help - show this output&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)\n    print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;add a b [b ...] - add row a to all rows indexed b&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)\n    print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;move a b - move row a before row b&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)\n\n\n\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Edef\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"font-weight: bold\"\u003Emain\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003Cspan style=\"\"\u003E(matrix_input)\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E -&gt; \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ENone\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    matrix = [line \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E line \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E matrix_input]\n\n    first_time = \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ETrue\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n    \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ewhile\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003ETrue\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n        show(matrix)\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E first_time:\n            show_help()\n            first_time = \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003EFalse\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Etry\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n            cmd = input(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;&gt; &quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eexcept\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E KeyboardInterrupt:\n            \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ebreak\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Etry\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n            cmd, *args = cmd.split()\n            \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E cmd == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;help&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n                show_help()\n            \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eelif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E cmd == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;add&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n                a = int(args[\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(255, 205, 34)\"\u003E0\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E])\n                \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(129, 142, 150)\"\u003E# Use a list comprehension to force it to fail early\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\n                bs = [int(b) \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E b \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E args[\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(255, 205, 34)\"\u003E1\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:]]\n                \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Efor\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E b \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Ein\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E bs:\n                    matrix[b] = apply(matrix[a], matrix[b])\n            \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eelif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E cmd == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;move&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n                a, b = args\n                a, b = int(a), int(b)\n                row = matrix.pop(a)\n                matrix.insert(b, row)\n        \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eexcept\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n            print(\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;Error in command&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E)\n\n\n\u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(147, 199, 99);font-weight: bold\"\u003Eif\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E __name__ == \u003Cspan style=\"color: rgb(236, 118, 0)\"\u003E&quot;__main__&quot;\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E:\n    main(MATRIX_INPUT)\n\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fspan\u003E\u003C\u002Fcode\u003E\u003C\u002Fpre\u003E\u003Cdiv style=\"text-align: right; font-size: min(1.87vw, 70%); opacity: 0.7; margin-bottom: 1.7142857em;\"\u003Emade with @nex3's \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fnex3.github.io\u002Fcohost-highlight\"\u003Esyntax highlighter\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003C\u002Fdiv\u003E\n\n\u003C\u002Fdetails\u003E\n\nIn this case, I had to arbitrarily assign two of the variables, because this puzzles seems slightly under-constrained (I believe this means there are 4—very similar—valid solutions). Once you get a fully solved matrix out:\n\n\u003Cdetails\u003E\n\u003Csummary\u003EThe fully solved matrix\u003C\u002Fsummary\u003E\n\n```\n100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000010000000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000001000000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000100000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000010000000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000001000000000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000100000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000010000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000001000000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000100000000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000010000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000001000000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000100000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000010000000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000001000000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000100000000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000010000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000001000000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000100000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000010000000000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000001000000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000100000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000010000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000001000000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000100000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000010000000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000001000000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000100000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010000|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001000|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000100|1\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000010|0\n000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000000001|0\n```\n\n\u003C\u002Fdetails\u003E\n\nWe can pull the solution back out of this grid, taking the column on the right and wrapping it back up into a grid.\n\n\u003Cdetails\u003E\n\u003Csummary\u003E(Spoilers) The solution vector, as a board\u003C\u002Fsummary\u003E\n\n```\n000101\n110100\n010001\n000100\n110100\n010000\n110001\n010110\n110100\n```\n\n\u003C\u002Fdetails\u003E\n\nAnd that works perfectly :D\n\nOne final note: This suggests a hell method for producing these puzzles.\nAny solvable linear system here generates a puzzle.\nFor this one, since everything only affected its neighborhood, the matrix was very sparse.\nBut if you made an extremely non-sparse matrix, you'd get any cell potentially toggling any other cell.\nEnjoy :)","postingProject":{"projectId":6601,"handle":"porglezomp","displayName":"cassie","dek":"witch of light","description":"I like, programming languages, compilers, types, formal logic, girls, video games, computer graphics, databases, sci-fi (and also just, everything). White. 26.\r\n\r\nSee @cassie-gundam for Gundam posts.","avatarURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Favatar\u002F6601-a2629af8-0512-4206-a23e-49542bc7e118-profile.jpg","avatarPreviewURL":"https:\u002F\u002Fstaging.cohostcdn.org\u002Favatar\u002F6601-a2629af8-0512-4206-a23e-49542bc7e118-profile.jpg","headerURL":null,"headerPreviewURL":null,"privacy":"public","url":"https:\u002F\u002Fwitchoflight.com\u002F","pronouns":"she\u002Fthey","flags":[],"avatarShape":"squircle","loggedOutPostVisibility":"public","frequentlyUsedTags":["cassie Gundam","g