            " class="h-full w-full object-cover" data-attachment-id="d816dd27-bb6e-4f03-a95a-dac7ba8d6d0a" alt="A notebook spread written in blue pen, on the left side is a grid showing the puzzle, and then a bunch of smaller sub-grids that encode the affected areas of each piece. On the right page is part of the diagonal of a sparse binary matrix, but I&#x27;ve given up because it&#x27;s like 30% too big to easily fit on the page." title="A notebook spread written in blue pen, on the left side is a grid showing the puzzle, and then a bunch of smaller sub-grids that encode the affected areas of each piece. On the right page is part of the diagonal of a sparse binary matrix, but I&#x27;ve given up because it&#x27;s like 30% too big to easily fit on the page."/></button></div></div><div class="co-prose prose my-4 overflow-hidden break-words px-3"><p>I solved this puzzle properly, by hand! It only took like four hours.<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><p>You know there&#x27;s a simple algorithm for this puzzle: you just have to construct and solve a 54x54 linear system in ℤ₂! Each cell influences some subset of the other cells (and sets them to 1), so you make a column out of each cell to form a matrix 𝐀, as well as a vector for the solution 𝐛, and then solve 𝐀𝐱 + 𝐛 = 0 in ℤ₂.<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><p>More in-depth details below the cut, I&#x27;ll explain all of that at least <!-- --><em>briefly<!-- --></em> for folks who don&#x27;t know what those terms mean. And you won&#x27;t see the solution unless you want to, if you want to try this method for yourself.<!-- --></p></div><div class="co-prose prose my-4 overflow-hidden break-words px-3"><hr/>
<!-- --><p>The first part: we want to model toggling things on and off so we can handle the lights here.
Luckily, mathematicians have our back, the set of numbers ℤ₂ represents that well.
In it, there are only two numbers, 0 and 1, and addition works the same as usual except that 1 + 1 = 0 — so adding 1 to a number toggles it on and off.
Multiplying is completely normal.<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><p>Next, we need a bunch of equations to figure out whether each square is toggled.
We give each square a name so we can write about their relations:
Let&#x27;s say:<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><ul>
<!-- --><li>square 𝑥₀ is toggled by squares 𝑥₀, 𝑥₁, 𝑥₅, and 𝑥₈<!-- --></li>
<!-- --><li>it&#x27;s initially on in the puzzle<!-- --></li>
<!-- --><li>we want to turn it off (because it&#x27;s &quot;Lights Out&quot;)<!-- --></li>
<!-- --></ul>
<!-- --><p>We can write that equation as: 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₅ + 𝑥₈ + 1 = 0.
Conveniently, we can add 1 to both sides of this equation, and get 𝑥₀ + 𝑥₁ + 𝑥₅ + 𝑥₈ = 1, which is slightly nicer to work with later.
We can make one equation like this for each cell in the grid, and then solve them all simultaneously.<!-- --></p>
<!-- --><p>Let&#x27;s find an actual one of these equations, looking at the very first cell:<!-- --></p>
